The program crashes because the `crc8` function performs an out-of-bounds read on the input buffer. Specifically, in `program.c` at line 11, the `for` loop condition `i <= len` causes the loop to execute when `i` equals `len`. Since the buffer `buf` is indexed from `0` to `len - 1`, accessing `buf[len]` results in an out-of-bounds read.

ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:11` contains an off-by-one error in the loop condition `i <= len`. The loop should iterate exactly `len` times (for `i` from `0` to `len - 1`) to process the input buffer, but the `<=` operator allows the index `i` to reach `len`, which is one past the end of the `buf` array, causing a heap-buffer-overflow.

LOCAL FIX: Change the loop condition from `i <= len` to `i < len` in `program.c`.
